- no need to update getLogModuleNumber() and LoggerModuleNumberToName() function in ServiceManager.c file ?

due to the new 1st line, is it possible to enlarge the colums to respect the vertical alignment which was existing before ?
Not a great fan of this
Is there any other way of dealing with this ?

The more elegant solution is to remove such HWL wrapper files for PHY files, 
and use legacy PHY makefiles to compile them.

As this will need extra work (makefiles +  more adaptation in PHY source code for log and other external services), 
I suggest to handle this comment later, if I have enough time before leaving to do so.

Are you, and Franck, OK ?

did you check that compile with no SIERRA flag is still functional ?

I am not PHY expert, maybe this file is not used when SIERRA is not defined, so I guess no issue.

PHY/... files are RF related files imported from PHY releases for SWI 2G PHY to MAC RF driver port purpose.

So they are not used with undefined SIERRA flag, so you're right, there is no issue.
this extra space at the end of line is not required

did you check that compile with no SIERRA flag is still functional ?

Flagging the fix to ease further Altair updated PHY code merges

commits.commitMessage:
[MAC/BSP TCOM] Workaround for demo EC CC1 due to DSP limitation (ECGSM-25)

Description:
  - Do not activate DSP IR management thanks to compilation flag _HWL_DISABLE_EGPRS_IR in BSP_TOM.mk
  - Use compilation flag _ECPACCH_AND_ECPDTCH_NOT_SUPPORTED_SIMULTANEOUSLY in SWIR_2GTelecomStack.mk to use EC-PDTCH only decoding mode during EC downlink transfer until final ack is received, and use EC-PACCH only decoding mode in other cases
  - Add possible (not activated) "__EGPRS_MSCLASS__=1" compilation flag to enable EGPRS class 1 in protocol stack for Mcs1 test purpose
  - Do not test MeanBep for block validity.
  - Use MCS1-4 USF metric to determine USF validity if CS 4 is detected by DSP in EGPRS mode (for MCS1 test purpose)
  - Add EC-PDTCH and EC-PACCH global BSP/DSP unitary test under compilation flag __HWL_VALIDATION_SEQUENCER__ and __HWL_DSP_UT_RX_SEQUENCER__ (not activated by default)

Change-Id: I0dfc667021230ce11ad1e3baa3859bdc64745195
Resolves: ECGSM-25
commits.subject: [MAC/BSP TCOM] Workaround for demo EC CC1 due to DSP limitation (ECGSM-25)

comments.message: This variable could be removed since its content is not used.
Header is not used. Those lines could be removed.

This is not correct. 

according to 3GPP 44.060 10.3.1.3. USF is not part of the MAC header. It is encoded separately.

In that case (EC-PACCCH/D with 75 bits), we should better have OutDecCtrlBlockInd->Data = &rrm_Glb->RecMsg->Body.Ph_PacketRxCtrlInd.Data[0] OutDecCtrlBlockInd->CurrentOffset = 5 (MAC header size)

When changing the CSN1 descriptions files, please also take care to provide the generated .h and .c files in the folder \mac\Device\PS100\SWIR\modem\csn1_out\

If new definitions are missing in those files, the GCC compilation will fail when ran under Windows host.

(When building the embedded firmware with GCC under Linux Host, the CSN1 .c and .h files generation from .csn file is correctly performed, there is no such issue).

comments.message: Please remove all trailing spaces introduced by your mods
Is this mod related to fixed JIRA ticket ?
Yes: this E2P field stores the T3314 Ready timer, which is involved in the PSM feature by the way that T3324 Active Timer starts when T3314 expires.
Please remove all trailing spaces introduced by your mods

What is it ?
An error to indicate that the value we wanted to write is already in place in NVM ?

Really usefull ?
What would the user do with this indication ?
In case, user can read the current value and compare to the write candidate value,
rather to try it and read the "error".

NOTE: This added symbol seems not to be used by FMS AL code ... ?? ==> To be removed ??

This define is used in mmp_PsmSetCfg() function.
Reminder : All PSM source code is imported from a product based on AR6220 product.
On AR6220, the E2P write operation could provide these both value when a writting operation was considered as successfull : FMS_OK or FMS_NO_CHANGE. FMS_NO_CHANGE was returned when the value to be written was already present in NV memory. On AR6220 product, a cache was used for FMS. It seems that NV memory was cached. For a writting operation, the content to be written was compared to the cached, and only really written in NV memory if this content was different than the data present in cache. If data was the same, FMS_NO_CHANGE was returned. It had to be considered as a successfull writting operation in the caller's point of view.

When FMS was merged on HL7802, it seems that this angle of the FMS fearure was not taken into account, so you are right, FMS_NO_CHANGE is not significant in HL7802 as never produced by FMS on HL7802.

I will remove this added define and will modify the location where it is used (mmp_PsmSetCfg() function).

I could let this patch unchanged : there is no issue : I used it by using also FMS_OK : 
'if(( FMS_OK == RetE2P ) || ( FMS_NO_CHANGE == RetE2P ))'
-> this returned value FMS_NO_CHANGE is never produced and replaced by FMS_OK, so test for the 'if' is the same.

Well done to update unit tests for FMS :-)
(even if it is no longer currently used, that might be usefull one day ... ;-)

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(17 comments)

Hi,

Please see my comments below.

In additions, could you please add a unit test scenario that implements the normal uplink TBF release. Indeed, the two scenarios that you created only tested the abnormal release of TBF, not the normal use case. 
(TestEcPUAN checked the T3238 expiry and TestEcContFail checked the T3228 expiry). To do that, please see my comments in GenTestEcPUAN.c. You can reuse this test scenario and enhances it to reproduce the normal TBF release.
You basically need to add the MAC_START_TBF_RELEASE_REQ in the test sequence and then upon T3228 expiry, PH_CCCH_REQ should be sent to L1.
Have a look at legacy GPRS/EGPRS uplink TBF release test scenarios to reproduce the same flow. Basically upon (EC-)PUAN with final ack, you should sent (EC-)Packet Control Ack (PH_PACKET_TX_CTRL_REQ), upon confirmation of L1 sending of (EC-)Packet Control Ack, i.e. RR reception of PH_PACKET_TX_CTRL_CNF, RR releases the TBF (in rrt_UL_TransA2())
Then finally RR sends PH_CCCH_REQ to L1 and L1 stops listening to (EC-)PACCH. 
This is the normal release of TBF. For EC-TBF, you basically need to wait for T3238 expiry before sending PH_CCCH_REQ in rrt_UL_TransA2()

You should not observe an abnormal release in the test scenario ("Abnormal release RRT_ERR_34h" observed in TestEcPUAN.trc)

Regards,
Ludovic HAESSLER

comments.message: this new comment is useless as no prototypes are added after

Let's study the folloowing case : 
previously, PS2GAL has sent a shutdown request to other tasks.
Among these tasks, if one has a lower priority than PS2GAL, then the shutdown request will be treated by this task after PS2GAL has completed its action, so at least after this present function ps2gal_StopStackComplete(). So PS2GAL calls directly (so in the PS2GAL task process) the function to release resources when the shutdown request may be not yet treated by the task with lower priority. That means that ressources in this task will be released when task has not yet treated the shutdown process.
-> we are releasing resources which are currently still in use has the task is not stopped.

To avoid such a situation, the resources of a task X should be released by the task X itself, when the shutdown request gas been received (typically, after the while(1) of the task X.

So, 
- call to rrm_ReleaseAllResources() should be removed from here and moved in rr_task() function after the while(1).

- call to mms_ReleaseAllResources() should be removed from here and moved in mm_task() function after the while(1).

->This design is the one used by CC, and is also the one suggested initially by Stéphane, instead of driving the release resources operation from PS2GAL.

Totally agree, and as you mentioned, I proposed this the first time.

But it's not what I was asked to do, and it does not concern MM/GMM only. So I will have to modify code from other S.E. with a MM/GMM related ticket. Not very clean, isn't it ?

So, if it is absolutely necessary, you should open a new ticket explaining the case, otherwise it will stay as it is.

comments.message:
Why CC's ressources are freed inside CC task, when RR and MM/GMM ressources are freed by calling procedure from PS2GAL ?
It would be coherent to have a similar procedure for all task.

CC is self-defined while GRR and GMM are made of a set of submodules.
So it makes sense to gather the release of the resources for GRR & GMM, while it is just cosmetics concerning CC.
And as you noted, it would have been coherent to do the same for all tasks (of all modules), but it isn't even the case.

better : 
/* To be able to restart stack later */
Correction: the stack restarts even without this procedure call but the module can reattach itself. This call has been specifically introduced to be able to reattach.
I don't understand : the function mmc_Terminate() performs the mmc_Global deallocation, isn't it ? SO why this comment ?
Oups... Forget to remove the comment...

mmc_init() is called from several point, and maybe two mmc_init() calling may occurs.
So this allocation will be done several times ...

Right... But then, I will ask when/where should I initialize the pointer to NULL value. But the way the pointer is declared prevent any initialization.
Besides, I think the problem isn't the double allocation... It   comes from the fact the initialization function is called twice... :)
So I guess that I 'll have to flag the code with a boolean.
There is another solution which involves introspection but will require to alter slighty the data structure, but will definitely solve this kind of issues if it is applied to every  structures... :)
I should stop dreaming... ^^

Initialization is supposed to be done one time when task is initialized, not each time we enter in mmc_RetrieveEvent() function (this function is called each time a incoming message is received by MMC). 
I understand that a protection is done in mmc_InitArrays() to perform the initialization only one time, but it is more logical to move this call where the task init is done.
Right. And if things were done correctly, those arrays should be part of the global MMC structure. Just saying... :)
Yep, forgot to remove the comment.Besides should flag the code because it may be called twice... Nice !!!
If a task stop is received, the message in MMC and MMP queues (managed by mms_RetrieveEvent()) shall be delete, no ? It is not done.

There is no need of releasing a "is_task_ended" type message as on one hand, this one has no payload, on another hand, the message header is stored in a local variable.
Maybe I missed something but I don't see what...

This function is supposed to be called from ps2gal_StopStackComplete function.
I was assured by someone (I let you guess who ^^) that every intermediate allocated resource was released before reaching the function. And the only job was in fact to release the bigger data structure.
Was it bulls..t or did things changed in the meantime ?

Check on rac is necessary to manage the case where the rac string would not be filled (='\0).
This case should not occur, but as rac is provided by other software component than AT, we have to manage all cases.

the variable is at_db_info.at_db_command_state[CGREG_STATE].cmdlist.
This variable is used. 
But effectively, the fields cmdlist[2], ..., cmdlist[7] are not used but as they are existing, it is better to initialize them in case where someone will use them in the future

1- AT database variables should be initialized in AT_DB.c

2- May be I'm wrong , but I think that cmdlength = 1 means that only cmdlist[0] will be used for CGREG command. in the code cmdlist[1] is used too.

1- I copied / paste what has been done by Altair in AT_CMD_HANDLER(CEREG), where this initialization is done here.
I guess it is not done in at_DB.c because this initialization is done here only in case where no parameters is provided bu user.

2 - same remark as point 1) : I copied / paste what Altair has done, I guess they are right.
I don't know exactly how to use the cmdlength, but I follow how Altair use it in CEREG

the cases where CoverageClass equals to PH_CC2 or PH_CC3 is not managed.
In such a situation, the value for BurstType will be PH_TX_AB_8,a s defined line 856.
-> Is it normal/expected ?

Yes, for the demo only CC1 and CC4 are supported.

User is not supposed to configure CC2 nor CC3. If he does, he will be punished and a 8 bits random access burst will be sent.

Note: in a real EC-GSM implementation, all this piece of code would be removed.

comments.message: PH_TX_AB_11_TS7 shall be defined for CC4

shall be training sequence 7 not 4 for CC4

add also a comment '(Coverage Class 4)'
please remove this "#if 0", see below comment

This piece of code is no more needed for GRR unit tests, please remove it.

Indeed, a previous delivery (https://gerrit-legato/#/c/external/altair/1250/mac/+/27561/) fixed the GRR unit tests failures.

See also Jira Ticket https://issues.sierrawireless.com/browse/ALT1250-1028

Question: Why do you perform this mask?
Can you put a comment in the code? Thanks

this condition shall be replaced by 'if (rrm_Glb->EcGsmIoT.EcTbfRunning)'

This variable rrm_Glb->EcGsmIoT.EcTbfRunning indeed ensures that the TBF requested by RLU is for an EC-TBF.

If using condition ' if (rrm_Glb->EcGsmIoT.DemoMode == RRM_EC_GSM_DEMO_ACTIVE)' that may lead to errors since this condition can be true in case of NAS signalling (GPRS attach,PDP context activation,...) and DemoMode configured through AT command. But NAS signalling shall use regular TBF, not EC-TBF.
According to selected Coverage class (CC1 or CC4), TS3 or TS7 shall be used. ( based on rrm_Glb->EcGsmIoT.CoverageClass)
Seems to be not used in the code. Correct?
pL1c->Uplink.Ec.DlCoverageClass to be added and used
PH_EC_UPLINK value should be used for EC-TBF and use in the code , see gl1cprot.hi

Uplink allocation shall be filled using these parameters in pL1c->Uplink.Ec structure:
 u8    NbBlockAllocated;  /* Nb block to transmit before waiting PUAN */
  u8    DelayNextUlRlcDataBlock;
  u8    NbRepeatAlloc;     /* temporary - for UL demo, correspond to nb systematic L3 repetition */
  u8    DelayRepeatAlloc;  /* temporary - for UL demo, gap in UL opportunity between end of allocation and next repetition */

For EC-GSM fixed allocation information, do not use
pL1c->Uplink.Fixed structure. This structure is an old structure used for old GPRS fixed allocation (feature currently removed from 3GPP specs).

You need to use the structure pL1c->Uplink.Ec, see ExtendedCoverageUplink_t in gl1cprot.hi

See also rrt_PhPacketTransferReq() function that contains some code already used for EC-GSM demo we did in 2016. Maybe this code has to be updated to match the need of our future EC-GSM demo

look for 
SendMsg->Body.Ph_PacketTransferReq.Uplink.Ec...

#elif 
#define RR_GET_MT(_v_)          GETMSK8(_v_, 0, MASKL6)
#endif /*__NO_EC_GSM_IOT__*/

commits.commitMessage:
Dynamic allocation of GRR.

Replace "return" with "SYS_ASSERT" when ke_Malloc returns NULL.
Replace "SYS_ASSERT" by "SYS_ASSERT_STRING".
Compilation OK.
Update ke_InMail_t structure for shutdown broadcasting.
Correction of unitary test (GenTC_42_4_2_2_1).
Create a new 12k item memory pool.
Implement the release of resources for each submodules of GRR.
Gather all release procedures calls into the rrm_ReleaseAllResources
function.
Mark part of the code with *INDENT-OFF* & *INDENT-ON* tags to prevent
future formatting by astlyle.
Update the RTX wrapper for ke_Free function to get unitary tests built.
Implement tasks destruction.
Add PS2GAL task to the list of authorized message emitters for PS2GSIM.
Disable the shutdown procedure as CGATT does not report attachment.
Change the module id of the debug traces within each task to have
unitary tests compiled.
Make changes to remove warnings issued during the unitary tests
compilation.
Modify the unitary test mailbox reception function in order to prevent
any shutdown request as this one is not supported yet.

Resolves: ALT1250-785

comments.message:
if SIERRA code is not embedded, the build will fail because in such a case, ps2gal_wrap.c file is not compiled/linked, so function present in ps2gal_wrap.c will not be defined although they are called by AT.

Solution is : 

LDFLAGS = \
    $(ARCH_CFLAGS) \
    -Wl,--gc-sections \
    -Wl,--no-insn32 \
    -Wl,-e,_start \
    -u _start \
    -u _InterruptVector \
    -Wl,-Map=$(PLATFORM).map \
    -T $(LDFILE)

# SWISTART
ifeq ($(WITH_SIERRA),true)
LDFLAGS += \
    -Wl,--wrap,is_attached_combined \
    -Wl,--wrap,isNasRegistered
endif
# SWISTOP
please move this variable outside the descriptor section

this file is organized as following : 
- the descriptor for sending messages (ps2gal_DscSndMsg_Dyn_t) are together
- the descriptor for receiving messages (ps2gal_DscRcvMsg_Dyn_t) are together

your delivery mix sending and receiving descriptors.
-> please separate sending and receiving by keeping the current organization
Please move this variable outside the descriptor section
it seems this include is only used by ps2gal_sms.c, so it is not justified to add this include here : prefer to add it in ps2gal_sms.c file
please keep the alignment with other message descriptors
please keep the alignment with other message descriptors

what happen if a 2nd NAS_MO_RL_DATA_REQ incomes when a MO SMS req  procedure is running ?

ps2gal_SaveSmsMtMoInfo.MO_Message_Reference  will be overwritten by the 2nd SMS ...
start description by indicating that this function is used to manage NAS_MO_RL_DATA_REQ reception from AT
does it contain length of  SC address ?
yes, this is the field Length of the SC address

Some sanity checks to checks validity of datas provided by altair could be useful : 
- if pEncoded_TPDU->UDL !=0 and pEncoded_TPDU->UD == NULL  -> abnormal -> ERROR
- if pEncoded_TPDU->UDL ==0 -> log a warning trace
- if pEncoded_TPDU->DA_Address == NULL -> ERROR
- if pEncoded_TPDU->DA_Address[0] == 0 -> log a warning trace
I understand that this parameter is used to build the response. What does this parameter mean ?
if this parameter is different from NULL, the response to the NAS_MO_RL_DATA_REQ will be treated by AMA instead of the USER AT command

could be done in one instruction : 
pData = (u8 *)&ps2gal_PtrMsgSnd->Body.SmsMoReq + sizeof(wm_sms_MoReq_t);
start description by indicating that this function is used to manage WM_SMS_SERV_RSP reception from SMS (SWI) layer
use an ERROR macro for this case
why using an argument if only NAS_MO_REPORT_IND messageid is managed ?
I intended to remove this argument in the next delivery (SMS Part 2 : memory availability).

in altair definition, we have : 'nRP_Error = 5, //NW to ms'
So it seems this error is dedicated to NW to ms echange.

If ps2gal_SmsMoReqFailed() function is called by ps2gal_Rec_NasMoRlDataReq(), error is due to failure in ps2gal_SendBuffer() or ps2gal_ResBuffer(), so there is no exchange NW -> MS. 

So, is pRP_Response->RP_Type = nRP_Error; a correct value ?
you are right but this value has been chosen intentionally
not necessary as immediately set just after
start description by indicating that this function is used to manage WM_SMS_MT_IND reception from SMS (SWI) layer
can you justify to me this implementation ? (what does n=1 mean ?)

this implementation is based on what I read from the code received from ALTAIR 

n = 1 means that delivery report comes from SMSManager without error
can you explain to me how do you know that the cause is present in TP_UD[1] ?
Describe these arguments in the 'variable name section' in the header description just above.

sanity check : check that : 
- if Len !=0 and Data ==NULL, -> ERROR trace
start description by indicating that this function is used to manage WM_SMS_MT_END_IND reception from SMS (SWI) layer

Yes, now, this can occur.
Exemple : 
1) MS is switched on : PS2GAL receives NAS_CFUN_1_TRIGGER_IND from AT. This was not introduced by this delivery, it was already implemented before.
2) 2G part started due to NAS_CFUN_1_TRIGGER_IND reception (PS2GAL and 2G protocol stack are running). This was not introduced by this delivery, it was already implemented before.
3) AT+CFUN=0 (new feature in this delivery). 2G stack layers are stopped, but the task are still alive, they are destroyed
4) AT+CFUN=1 -> PS2GAL receives NAS_CFUN_1_TRIGGER_IND from AT. This was not introduced by this delivery, it was already implemented before.
5) as in step2, 2G part is started : we enter again in function ps2gal_CreateProtoTasks(). As 2G tasks are alive (creation done in step 2), they will finally no new creation.

commits.commitMessage:
Correct missing Altair's and SWI traces.

Shift log modules indexes to avoid a "gap" resulting in missing traces
despite right configuration.
Develop the SWILogModuleIdChecker.py script automating the process generating pseudo-traces allowing to check whether a gap is
present within the range of module indexes. This is coupled with flagged
code (SWI_TEST_CHECKING_MODULES_IDS) present in the ps2gal_SystemInit
function. Flag can be set in the DragonFly.mk makefile.
Remove the ability to configure SWI traces through Altair's AT commands
at least for each module index bigger than 50. Configuration of those
modules are done with SWI AT commands (at+w[gsr]tl).
Modify the trcclean.sh script to prevent the output of error messages
when there is no traces files to clean.
Develop the SWILogDBFilter.py script automating the extraction of Altair's traces present in
binary objects whose code file is missing. The script need to be
launched at least once for each Altair's delivery. The result is stored
in the versioned LTELogDB_Altair.txt file stored in the
Tools/Logger/ConstDB folder.
Modify the set of scripts used to generate the binary images in order to
incorporate the mentioned scripts hereabove.

Resolves: ALT1250-768
Change-Id: I43f709147c2db16f39f931c3813ba4ef2e48760c
commits.subject: Correct missing Altair's and SWI traces.

Due to change in NAS_types.h by altair (see my previous comment), adaptatations are required regarding to 'operatorinfo' field in 'tNAS_PLMN_IND' structure.

Indeed, before Altair change, no need to allocate memory. Now, as operatorinfo is non more a tab but a tab of pointer, some allocation are required.
We can see, for example in AT_Handle_NAS_PLMN_Selection_Ind function, that after Altair's change, there is now a memory deallocation of operatorinfo[]. this deallocation was not present before. Thats means memory allocation is required now
-> some changes have to be made where msg sending using tNAS_PLMN_IND (NAS_PLMN_SELECTION_IND for example) is implemented (PS2GAL).
To be studied.

1) as 'NbPlmn' field is a u8 in structure 'wm_rr_PlmnListInd_t'
and as there is the following instruction : 
NbrPlmn = ps2gal_PtrMsgRec->Body.RrPlmnListInd.NbPlmn;

2) and as field 'numelemnts' is an U8 in the structure 'List_of_Operator"'
and as there is the following instruction  :
pNAS_PLMN_IND->operator_list.numelemnts = NbrPlmn;

->  NbrPlmn should be declared as an 'U8' or 'u8', but not as an 'int'
To avoid confusion, prefer to use an other pointer, to be declared with name pNAS_PLMN_SEL_IND

be careful : not sure this copy is really secured. You should prefer to use a memcpy by using pointeur on the structure.
But no need to change it : keep this notes into account for your other future development. 
MM/GMM uses alsso this method, so it seems to be OK, but using a memcpy is safer.

tested OK in Unix with source code got by using git client directly in Unix (and not from git client in windows as done in previous comment).

But a remark : the format of the build time is different in Windows and Unix, and probably also may depend on the configuration of time parameter in the unix machine : 
about swi_version_time.h file
in windows, the define SW_BUILD_TIME is equal to : 
#define SW_BUILD_TIME ("01_26_2018_01_05")
-> format is mm_dd_yyyy_hh_mm

in unix (Xbuntu), we have : 
Unix Xubuntu
#define SW_BUILD_TIME ("janv._26_2018_14_42_53")
-> format is month_dd_yyyy_hh_mm_ss
-> format is different.

these define, typedef etc... are supposed to be declared in some header files.
In Sierra, here are the rules we use : 
Organisation des fichiers header *.h*

*.hi : interface ...
*.ht : typedef, structure, type ...
*.ho : comme les *.hi = interface ...
*.hc : constante, enum (à confirmer), define ...
*.hv : variable, tableau de const ...
*.hm : macros
*.hp : prototypes de fonctions

before, _TRACE was wrongly formatted : 3 arguments were traced in the string, but only two variables were provided. So there was an error : size =%d was not  related to any variable.
Now, 3 variables are provided.
Is pPhyCmdConsole->header.length really the correct variable related to size = %d  ?

I hope it is right, otherwise it would mean that LHA was wrong... :)
Actually, I asked him to give me the right variable...

I would create a new define LOGGER_SWI_LAST_MODULE to be used here. 
# define LOGGER_SWI_LAST_MODULE   LOGGER_SWI_CORK_MODULE

that would be : for(i = LOGGER_SWI_FIRST_MODULE; i <= LOGGER_SWI_LAST_MODULE; i++)

Using this new define will manage the fact that ALtair could add some new module with index > LOGGER_SWI_LAST_MODULE

Concerning your last comment, I hope not, because firstly it would make the modifications useless and therefore I would have to recode everything concerning this patch, which is a workaround and not a correction.
Secondly, it would unnecessarily complexify the code.
Thirdly, I doubt that Altair may declare further modules with indexes higher than DOP_MAX_NUMBER_OF_LOG_ENTITIES (50), simply because they won't be able to store them. This is the purpose of this workaround.
Last but not least, they don't have any clue about our modules. They don't integrate our code, we are. That's why there is a LOGGER_SWI_FIRST_MODULE and not a LOGGER_SWI_LAST_MODULE, because this last one is LOG_MODULES_LIST_SIZE.

According to my experience, a altair trace would not be logged if an instruction is present in the same line than the ALTAIR macro (SWIERR_0 here), before this instruction.

Example : 
XXXX  ALTAIR_MACRO_TRACE()  -> not logged
/* YYYYY */  ALTAIR_MACRO_TRACE-> not logged

To solve this restriction, isolate the SWIERR_0 instruction :
if(xxxxx)
   SWIERR_0(yyyy)

You are right...
But remember, that, actually, Altair does not parse our traces anymore. We do, by generating our own traces dictionary.
This way, it's more flexible.
OK if our parsing manage correctly this use case
